# Project Instructions

## Build

```bash
# Fill from project inspection
# npm run build
# npm run test
# npm run lint
```

## Architecture

- Record only non-obvious boundaries Codex must preserve.
- Prefer references to existing docs over long summaries.
- Do not duplicate rules already enforced by tooling.

## Harness

### Trace Root

Use `{TRACE_ROOT}` for harness history:

```text
{TRACE_ROOT}/evolution/     # Harness change history
{TRACE_ROOT}/failures/      # Failure diagnosis with raw context
{TRACE_ROOT}/experiments/   # Autoresearch episodes
{TRACE_ROOT}/search-set.md  # Active verification cases
```

### Change Strategy

Use additive changes first, subtractive changes second, structural changes last. Keep one functional harness change per iteration so regressions are attributable.

### Verification

Before and after harness changes, run Active verify commands from `{TRACE_ROOT}/search-set.md` when practical. Record PASS/FAIL and key output lines in the related evolution trace.

### Failure Recording

Record failures that require causal reasoning, produce results opposite to hypothesis, or reveal a new guard violation type. Do not record simple typos or obvious one-off fixes.

### Structural Escalation

Recurring failures should move from instructions to tooling, CI, generated artifacts, or other structural prevention. Prefer "cannot happen" over "remember not to do it."

## Codex Notes

- Codex does not use Claude Code slash commands or `.claude/settings.local.json` hooks.
- Use explicit verification commands unless project tooling provides stronger enforcement.
